sfqid %>% group_by(Patient, Region) %>% summarise(SumReadNums = sum(ReadNums)) %>% ggplot(aes(x= SumReadNums))+ geom_histogram()

sfqid %>% group_by(Patient, Region) %>% summarise(SumReadNums = sum(ReadNums)) %>% unite(PatientRegion, Patient, Region) %>% ggplot(aes(x= PatientRegion, y=SumReadNums))+ geom_bar(stat="Identity") + coord_flip()

sfqid %>% group_by(Patient) %>% summarise(numregions = n()/3) %>% ggplot(aes(x= Patient, y=numregions))+ geom_bar(stat="Identity")

This next step createsa bash script that will merge the 3 fastq technical replicates into files into a single patient_region fastq file. I add P and R for patient and region - fo rclarity and because it is poor housekeeping to have filenames beginning with numbers (bash and R have problems)

sfqid %>% 
  group_by(Patient, Region) %>% 
  summarise(allSampleID = paste0(sampleID, collapse =",")) %>% 
  separate(allSampleID, into=c("S1", "S2", "S3"), sep =",")%$%
  paste0("cat ", S1, ".fastq.gz, ", S2, ".fastq.gz, ", S3, ".fastq.gz, ", "> P", Patient, "_R", Region, ".fastq.gz")
